caption: Tacos are super dry and served lukewarm. Tacos are not worth the price or the price of parking.

The food is delicious, albeit quite expensive. My complaints come from my bad experience using the DoorDash app to order from them. I ordered my food using the app around 7:20pm, and I will admit that they were very busy on this night. The app told me that my estimated pickup time would be around 7:45pm. 7:45pm came and went, and still no update on the app. There is a shelf where almost every other restaurant in Time Out Market places DoorDash orders for people to come pick up, and I have had good experiences using this pickup method from other vendors in Time Out Market. I went to go check on the shelf multiple times, and my order was never there. It was only at 8:05pm when I got fed up waiting and went up to the counter to see if they missed my order or something. When I asked, they promptly grabbed my food and gave it to me. This was exceedingly frustrating because the food that was given to me was a bag that had been sitting on a side counter, NOT under heat lamps, for over 20 minutes. My order WAS ready on time, but they did not update my DoorDash order, so I had no way of knowing that the food sitting on the counter was mine, and I did not know when to pick it up. After handing me my order (which was cold at this point... especially disappointing because it was a quesadilla), the staff THEN updated DoorDash, so on my end I got the notifications that my food was ready to pick up and that the order had been fulfilled simultaneously. I love this business, but I would not recommend anybody use DoorDash to order from them, and I would request that Taqueria El Barrio PLEASE educate your staff better on how to use DoorDash so that you actually notify people when their orders are ready to pick up.

There is a self-serve station with different sauces of varying spiciness and a bowl of limes, too, which is nice.
New place on the block has great food and service. My new favorite taco spot !
Amazing tacos and sauces! Super recommend

Embarrassingly poor service and mediocre tacos.  I called to place an order and could not get an answer. We had to go out anyway so we went and ordered in person. They weren't particularly busy so we thought nothing of it. They messed up our order by giving us an extra fish taco instead of a fish plate. I called to get the issue fixed or a refund and was told the cashier didn't know how do a refund and to come the next day before she hung up on me.  When taking the train another night, I saw employees gathered by the window and an empty shop so I decided to call to ask about the refund. The phone rang and rang and no one answered, while 4 employees chatted by the window.
The tacos are top notch, and I would rate this place 5 stars if not for the very high pricing. The torta was skimpy and felt like a rip off compared to the competition.

This place is AMAZING. A whole in the wall with best authentic flavours. Freshly made, good portion size. The quesadilla is wonderful. Combos include their own freshly made drinks with fresh salsa to your liking. Churros are fantastic.

I’d give Taqueria el Barrio a 3.5 but since Google Reviews doesn’t allow that I have to round down for the series of price increases. I went during opening week and grabbed a fish taco and a vegan chorizo taco. The vegan chorizo is LIT—spicy and packed with flavor. But, balancing that out, the fish taco was super dry and overcooked. I was able to overcome the dry fish by adding extra salsa—there’s a station after you order where you can load up more from mild to spicy.  As other local guides have commented, when this place opened you could get tacos for under $3 and it was a steal at that price. Now that the prices have gone up, it’s  hard to get out of there for less than $10. If I’m spending $10 on tacos, then I’m going to zip on over to Lone Star instead.

Wow. The chicken quesadilla was so tasty. It all was so fresh and flavorful. Simple ingredients with so much flavor. The carnitas was a nice flavorful pulled pork.  I haven’t had churro that didn’t taste like oil in forever. So these were such a treat. The chocolate sauce was not overly sweet. Soo good.

This is my favorite taco spot in Boston. It's the only place I know around here where the al pastor is on a schwarma spit and served with pineapple, Chilango style. The chicharron is outstanding, the salsas are unapologetically spicy, and even with all the wonderful flavors, it's the tortilla that stands out and holds its own. I'm constantly bugging my wife to go here.

Ok, so I work nearby and have eaten here 20+ times since it opened, including opening day -- and I can confirm that as of today (11/12/19) the prices have gone up at least 4 times, and it feels like the quantity of protein you get while ordering plates has been reduced since when it opened.  Also, what other reviewers are saying about the fish tacos being low quality is true, it's basically breaded fish-sticks.  If fish tacos is what you want then just down the street is Sunset Cantina, which has much better fish, made fresh, isn't breaded, costs the same, and the place has Taco Tuesdays (which this place does not).  Add to that the fact that their Asada steak has unchewable cartilage bits and is subpar in both quality and flavor when compared to Chipotle down the street.  This place is coasting on the good reviews on opening day, when the tacos were $2.75 and not $4, and plates were $8.50 and not $12.  Its not really a good deal on this food strip anymore.  I feel the only reasons to go here are the sauces, which are decent, and the El Pastor pork, and beef tongue, which aren't common, and this despite the El Pastor being atypically dry.  Everything else I've seen done both better and cheaper.

The food here is delicious and authentic with an excellent variety of comfort foods and definitely delivers on flavor no matter what you order. The crispy pork and crispy pork belly is incredible and I will 100% come back for it again. The vibe inside is clean, bright, colorful and modern.Also, churros.

Best taco joint so far in Boston. They have tacos, tortas, and quesadillas (no burritos!). We only had tacos and they were mostly great. I had a caramello (steak, refried beans, and cheese), a vegan chorizo, and a fish taco. My wife had two fish tacos. I thought the fish tacos we're good - not bad but not their specialty. The vegan chorizo was...vegan chorizo. Same as the supermarket. The caramello was exceptional!  A selection of salsas, none especially spicy. My favorite was the dried Chile puree. Chips were the one miss - baked instead of fried they were a little too hard.
Excellent food and vibe! 100% recommend this place!! The chorizos are ammmazingg too!!

Actually, I was not a Tacos fan. But!!!! They Taqueria El Barrio let me fall in love with Tacos and Tortas. I ordered pork belly tacos and grilled chicken tortas. Their drinks and sauces are amazing! They are so fresh, yummy and unforgettable! Undoubtedly, I will be back soon. Highly recommended visit Taqueria El Barrio in Boston.
I was disappointed when Dorado on Harvard Ave. closed recently, but Taqueria El Barrio more than makes up for the loss. Excellent food, great staff, and a perfect location.

The place is right around the corner from my work. My coworkers and I have been looking for this place to open since March. The  wait line was not that bad taking into consideration we went there at 12:30pm at busy lunch time! The food was very authentic, delicious, fresh and flavorful. We ordered all the tacos on the menu and 2 Tortas CHORIZO. We were quite impressed by the Chorizo preparation (vegetarian option). My coworkers truly enjoyed El PAstor, Asada,Carnitas and Chicharon tacos.  I loved the decor, especially the traditional telavera tile on the tables. We will be back to try their weekend specials and the traditional casadias. The place is right next to Dunkin Donuts and Anthony's Pizza and also has a plenty of outside sitting.
The Asada(Steak) Quesadilla is really good! The service is quick. Be sure to give this place a try!

This place is the real deal.  Even the water tastes good.   to mention the fish tacos taste like you are on the pier in San Diego.  The churros are just beyond and if you like idea of food heaven, drop by and die happy.

We went on a Saturday and I was excited to try the beef tongue which was a weekend special... but it turned out they didn't have any of the weekend specials... on a weekend. The pollo taco didn't have much flavor to it - it was mostly guac and the fish in the fish taco was way overcooked.

My wife and I learned of this place quite by chance. She being from Mexico and me having lived in Mexico for three years, we are always on the hunt for authentic Mexican tacos. This place checks all the boxes. First, the food quality is exceptional. Second, the restaurant offers a variety of tacos with your choice of corn (soft or hard) or flour. They also offer tortas (Mexican sandwich) and a selection of flavored waters. We both had a pescado (fish) taco. My wife and another al pastor while I opted for the chicharrón (crispy pork skin). Definitely get the chicharrón if you like pork - it’s amazing. We shared a torta with carnitas. It was delicious, and full as we were toward the end we did not leave anything on our plate. This was worth the drive to Boston from the Merrimack Valley area. We will be back!

Probably the worst tacos I've ever had here in Boston! Tried the chicken, pork belly, and fish tacos here. The fish tacos were super dry and flavorless, the pork was soft and mushy, and the chicken was mostly cheese and guac instead of chicken. Won't be coming again! Go elsewhere.

Consider me a taco connoisseur. I could live, breathe and die by tacos... if "death by tacos" were such a thing. My heritage, my California upbringing, my Hispanic family friends growing up, have all led me to a fascination, love, and appreciation of arguably Mexico's most emblematic dish, the beloved taco.  Which is why I had goosebumps walking into Taqueria el Barrio on its third day of operation, a new addition to Packard's Corner in Brighton. It's a start-up by the owner of well-known restaurants Bergamot (Sommerville) and Bisq (Cambridge) - neither of which has any Mexican showings. So I was, indeed, curious.  The line to wait was long, roughly 5 minutes. There was some confusion of wait staff and order takers as to who's orders were who's coming out of the open kitchen - notably because they do not take people's names at the time of paying at the register.  The dining area was clean. There are four (4) different salsas/sauces to be added to your dishes if you are so daring. For my palate, two were medium hot and two were spicy... but by New England standards, you would consider them to all fairly spicy. And for those that go too far with adding the heat, there's ice water available to go and guzzle down.  Go big or go home - I got four tacos: Asada, Carnitas, El Pastor (which is citrus-marinated carnitas), and Pollo. I consider these the "four basic taco-food groups" when trying new tacos.  By far, the Asada and Carnitas/El Pastor were the shining beacons. The Pollo was a bit too bland on my flavor meter... at least compared to the others on my plate. Guacamole for miles piled on my tacos! That was a surprise, and even more surprising - it almost overwhelmed my flavors. None had a notable marinate or sauce that made the tacos truly sing their highest possible notes. However, solid performances all around.  My friend got one asada torta (think a taco inside a bread bun), and that was loaded with the flavors I admittedly wished was packed into my tacos!  This place has the potential to become taco greatness. A few "newbie" kinks to work out, so I won't hold that against them until I update my review in a few months. They deserve your try. I'm betting most people will love them, and adore their decor, and enjoy their $3.25 taco prices, which for the size they come in, is a steal in Boston.

The vegan chorizo was too tough to chew, like stale jerky, which is a shame because the flavour was excellent. I'll probably give it another try because the restaurant is new, but for now it's 2 stars.
Delicious tacos!😎👌🏼

This place is simply amazing and vegetarian friendly: 2 tacos and a quesadilla that I ordered were authentic and delicious, sauces that came on the side complimented dishes well and I never thought that rice water could taste so well. I highly recommend and will come again to try their sandwiches.

The place is something Boston has been waiting forever to have. I was first in the line when they just opened and despite the wait I was quite surprised by  quality of their food. I had an El Pastor Torta and Taco chicharrón and el pollo. The portion was huge. The tacos were very juicy and flavorful! I also line the concept that you can eat as much sauces as you can and they all very authentic. I mean authentic (spicy  hot, not all of them). Wait till you try them! I wish this place good luck! They know what traditional Mexican food is about! 5+ star taco place!

Great flavors, super satisfying.  Traditional taqueria menu, with tortas and quesadillas to boot! Typical Boston street parking situation, so plan accordingly. However, B line passes right in front of it.

The service is great and my taco was even better! I really enjoyed the taco with pescado (fried fish). I was pleasantly surprised by the portion size; one taco is plenty for a light lunch. At less than $3 per taco, I can’t wait to try them all! Thank you to Servio and the rest of the team!  The churros are really great as well :)
